Of the three persons who are most prominent in the first fifteen years of the fifth century—Honorius the Roman Emperor, Alaric the King of the Visi- goths, and Stilicho the Vandal general of the Roman army—Stilicho alone is mentioned by name in our poem. In Book IL, lines 41-60, Rutilius attacks him in the most bitter manner, accusing him of treachery to the Empire, of betraying Rome to the barbarians, and of burning the Sibylline Books. The prose writers Zosimus and Orosius adopt a similar tone. Zosimus¹ accuses him in common with Rufinus —wh0, as minister for Arcadius, held in the East a position similar to that enjoyed by Stilicho in the West-of being accessible to bribes and of perverting justice. Orosius² accuses him of secking to make his son Eucherius Emperor, of making a secret compact with Alaric to the detriment of the Roman state, and of bringing into the Roman domain the Alans, Suevi, Vandals, and Burgundians.
